05524nam a22011775i 9780520929845DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696268  a97805209298457 a10.1525/97805209298452doi  a(DE-B1597)520030  a(OCoLC)58752357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS135.R9 4aDS135.R9bB275 2003 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a947.085/092aB2211 aBardach, Janusz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurviving Freedom :bAfter the Gulag /cKathleen Gleeson, Janusz Bardach. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (269 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1941, as a Red Army soldier fighting the Nazis on the Belarussian front, Janusz Bardach was arrested, court-martialed, and sentenced to ten years of hard labor. Twenty-two years old, he had committed no crime. He was one of millions swept up in the reign of terror that Stalin perpetrated on his own people. In the critically acclaimed Man Is Wolf to Man, Bardach recounted his horrific experiences in the Kolyma labor camps in northeastern Siberia, the deadliest camps in Stalin’s gulag system.In this sequel Bardach picks up the narrative in March 1946, when he was released. He traces his thousand-mile journey from the northeastern Siberian gold mines to Moscow in the period after the war, when the country was still in turmoil. He chronicles his reunion with his brother, a high-ranking diplomat in the Polish embassy in Moscow; his experiences as a medical student in the Stalinist Soviet Union; and his trip back to his hometown, where he confronts the shattering realization of the toll the war has taken, including the deaths of his wife, parents, and sister. In a trenchant exploration of loss, post-traumatic stress syndrome, and existential loneliness, Bardach plumbs his ordeal with honesty and compassion, affording a literary window into the soul of a Stalinist gulag survivor. Surviving Freedom is his moving account of how he rebuilt his life after tremendous hardship and personal loss. It is also a unique portrait of postwar Stalinist Moscow as seen through the eyes of a person who is both an insider and outsider. Bardach’s journey from prisoner back to citizen and from labor camp to freedom is an inspiring tale of the universal human story of suffering and recovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJewsxBiographyxSoviet Union. 0aJewszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aJews, PolishxBiographyxSoviet Union. 0aJews, PolishzSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPlastic surgeonsxBiographyxSoviet Union. 0aPlastic surgeonszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPolitical prisonersxBiographyxSoviet Union. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  abelarussian front.  abiography.  acitizen.  acourt martial.  adictator.  adiplomacy.  adiplomat.  afreedom.  agold mines.  agrief.  agulag.  ahard labor.  ahealing.  ainjured soldier.  akolyma.  alabor camps.  aloss.  amedical student.  amemoir.  amilitary.  amoscow.  anazis.  anonfiction.  apolish embassy.  apolitical prisoner.  apostwar moscow.  apostwar russia.  aprison system.  aprisoner of war.  aprisoner.  aptsd.  arecovery.  ared army.  aredemption.  arepression.  arussia.  arussian history.  asiberia.  asoldier.  asoviet union.  astalin.  astalinist moscow.  astalinist russia.  asuffering.  aussr.  awar hero.1 aGleeson, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Pr